<section xml:id="sec-matrices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Matrices</title>

 <p>
We defined a matrix in <xref ref="def-matrix"/> (see also the example following that definition), 
but we will repeat it here since now we are going to start studying them in detail.
</p>


<definition xml:id="def-matrix2">
<statement>
<p>
A <term>matrix</term> is a rectangular array of numbers.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
<term>Terminology:</term>
<ul>
<li>
<p>The numbers in the array are called the <term>entries</term> of the matrix.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>We usually denote matrices by the capital roman letters <m>A, B</m> or <m>C</m>. In other 
sources, it is also common to use <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>, where <m>M</m> is for `matrix'.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <term>size</term> of a matrix is <m>m\times n</m> if it has <m>m</m> rows and <m>n</m> columns.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <m>\vect{(i, j)}</m>-<term>entry</term> of a matrix <m>A</m> is the entry in the <m>i</m>th 
row and <m>j</m>th column of <m>A</m>, and it is denoted by <m>a_{ij}</m>. (Similarly, the 
<m>(i, j)</m>-entry of a matrix <m>B</m> is denoted <m>b_{ij}</m>, and so on.)
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A <term>row matrix</term> or <term>row vector</term> is a <m>1\times n</m> matrix, and 
a <term>column matrix</term> or a <term>column vector</term> is a <m>m\times 1</m> matrix.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-basic-matrices">
<statement>
<p>Consider the matrices
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  3
\end{bmatrix}
, \qquad \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 4\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
The first is a row matrix and the second is a column matrix.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
Notice how these special matrices look essentially the same as vectors.
</p>

