<p>
If <m>A</m> is an <m>m\times n</m> matrix, we can write
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  a_{11} \amp  a_{12} \amp  \cdots \amp  a_{1n} \\
  a_{21} \amp  a_{22} \amp  \cdots \amp  a_{2n} \\
  \vdots \amp  \vdots \amp  \ddots \amp  \vdots \\
  a_{m1} \amp  a_{m2} \amp  \cdots \amp  a_{mn}
\end{bmatrix}
</me>
We may also write
<me>
A = [a_{ij}] \qquad \text{or} \qquad A = [a_{ij}]_{m\times n}
</me>
for short. If the columns of <m>A</m> are the column vectors <m>\vect{a}_1</m>, 
<m>\vect{a}_2, \ldots,\vect{a}_n</m>, we may write
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  \vect{a}_1 \amp  \vect{a}_2 \amp  \cdots \amp  \vect{a}_n
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
If the rows of <m>B</m> are the row vectors <m>\vect{b}_1</m>, <m>\vect{b}_2, \ldots, 
\vect{b}_m</m>, we may write
<me>
B =
\begin{bmatrix}
  \vect{b}_1 \\
  \vect{b}_2 \\
  \vdots     \\
  \vect{b}_m
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-matrix-sizes">
<statement>
<p>
Find the size and the <m>(2, 1)-</m>entry of the following matrices.
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  2 \\
  4 \amp  0 \\
  6 \amp  -1
\end{bmatrix}
, \qquad B =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0  \amp  -1 \\
  3 \amp  4 \amp  -2 \amp  5
\end{bmatrix}
, \qquad C =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1  \amp  -1 \amp  2  \\
  -2 \amp  3  \amp  4  \\
  5  \amp  6  \amp  -7 \\
  -3 \amp  -4 \amp  8
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>
<p>Answer: <m>A</m> has size <m>3 \times 2</m> and <m>a_{21} = 4</m>, since this is the first 
entry of the second row. <m>B</m> is a <m>2\times 4</m> matrix and <m>b_{21} = 3</m>. <m>C</m> 
is a <m>4\times 3</m> matrix and <m>c_{21} = -2.</m>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
<term>More terminology:</term>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <term>square matrix</term> is a matrix of size <m>n \times n</m>, for some <m>n</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <term>diagonal entries</term> of a square matrix <m>A</m> are <m>a_{11}, a_{22}, \ldots, a_{nn}</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>A <term>diagonal matrix</term> is a square matrix in which all non-diagonal entries are zero
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <term>identity matrix</term> <m>I_n</m> is the <m>n\times n</m> diagonal matrix with all 
diagonal entries equal to 1
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>The <term>zero matrix</term> <m>0_{m\times n}</m> is the <m>m\times n</m> matrix with all 
entries equal to zero.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-matrix-concepts">
<statement>
<p>
Here are examples for each definition.
</p>
<tabular halign="left">
  <col halign="left"/>
  <col halign="center"/>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
        0 \amp 3 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      <m>A</m> is not square since it is <m>2\times 3</m>
    </cell>
  </row>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>B=\begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 4\\
        0 \amp 2 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 3
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      <m>B</m> is square with diagonal entries <m>1,2,3</m>. It is not diagonal since <m>b_{13}\ne 0</m>.
    </cell>
  </row>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>D=\begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp -3
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      <m>D</m> is diagonal with diagonal entries <m>2,0,-3</m>
    </cell>
  </row>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>I_2=\begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 1
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      This is the <m>2\times 2</m> identity matrix
    </cell>
  </row>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>I_3=\begin{bmatrix}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      This is the <m>3\times 3</m> identity matrix
    </cell>
  </row>

  <row>
    <cell>
      <m>0_{23}=\begin{bmatrix}
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </cell>
    <cell>
      This is the <m>2\times 3</m> zero matrix.
    </cell>
  </row>
</tabular>
</statement>
</example>

<definition xml:id="def-equality-of-matrices">
<statement>
<p>
Two <m>m \times n</m> matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <term>equal</term> if their 
corresponding entries are equal.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
In other words, <m>A = B</m> if and only if <m>a_{ij} = b_{ij}</m> for all 
<m>i = 1, \ldots, n</m>, <m>j= 1, \ldots, n</m>.
</p>


<example xml:id="ex-equal-matrices">
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>A = [a_{ij}]_{2\times 2}</m> where <m>a_{ij}=2^{i-1}3^{j-1}</m> and <m>B =
\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp  3 \\
  2 \amp  6
\end{bmatrix}
</m>. Then <m>A=B</m> because
<md>
<mrow>
a_{11} \amp  = 2^0 3^0 = 1 = b_{11}          \\
a_{12} \amp  = 2^0 3^1 = 3 = b_{12}          \\
a_{21} \amp  = 2^1 3^0 = 2 = b_{21}          \\
a_{22} \amp  = 2^1 3^1 = 6 = b_{22}.
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

